Analysis of mammary glands

Using DESeq2

Kasper D. Hansen

Fall 2022

Data

Analysis is based on the paper “RNA-seq analysis is easy as 1-2-3 with limma, Glimma and edgeR” by Law et al (2018, F1000Res).

Data is RNA-seq data from the mammary glands of female mice in triplicate.

Cells have been sorted into 3 cell populations: basal, luminal progenitors (LP) and mature luminal (ML)

In this instance, reads were aligned to the mouse reference genome (mm10) using the R based pipeline available in the Rsubread package (specifically the align function followed by featureCounts for gene-level summarisation based on the in-built mm10 RefSeq-based annotation).
— from Law et at

Notes

Our focus here is on the steps performed in a typical RNA-seq analysis with limma-voom. This is not a publication level analysis.

We only focus on 2 out of the 3 cell populations, to make things simple.

We don’t control for batch effects and we don’t model the fact that the cell populations are paired, in the sense that one sample has been sorted into three different populations.

Loading the data

We load the edgeR package and the data in the form of a RangedSummarizedExperiment which might be familiar. edgeR uses its own data structure, a DGEList.

library(DESeq2)
## Warning: package 'DESeq2' was built under R version 4.3.1

## Warning: package 'GenomeInfoDb' was built under R version 4.3.1

load("mamgland_rse.rda")

There are many (27k) genes

Making a DDS object

rse <- mamgland_rse[, mamgland_rse$group %in% c("Basal", "LP")]
dds <- DESeqDataSet(rse, design = ~ group)
## factor levels were dropped which had no samples
dds$group
## [1] LP    Basal Basal LP    Basal LP   
## Levels: Basal LP

We see that the reference level is Basal

PCA

For PCA to work well, it is usually a good idea to use a proper transformation on the data. Of particular concern for RNA-seq data are

  • The effect of library size (sequencing depth).
  • The mean-variance relationship.

One possibility is to apply a variance stabilizing transformation. We will avoid the details, but in DESeq2 there are two options rlog() (slower) and vst() (faster). We will use the former here.

rlog() produces data which is on the \(\log_2\)-scale and has been corrected for library size, so it is straightforward to use in a PCA.

rld <- rlog(dds, blind = TRUE)
plotPCA(rld, intgroup = "group")

In this plot, the axes are scaled by the amount of variation explained. This is a recommended visualization method, but often harder to do and most PCA plot you see, don’t do this.

Here, we see that group explains a whopping 98% of the variation. So either there is something wrong, or we are going to get a huge amount of differential expression.

Running DESeq2

We now run DESeq2. This is done by the results() function which performs a number of sequential tasks under the hood, including

  • expression filtering
  • dispersion (variance) shrinkage
  • testing
dds <- DESeq(dds)
## estimating size factors
## estimating dispersions
## gene-wise dispersion estimates
## mean-dispersion relationship
## final dispersion estimates
## fitting model and testing
resultsNames(dds)
## [1] "Intercept"         "group_LP_vs_Basal"
res <- results(dds)

Expression filtering

In DESe2, expression filtering happens by default using independent filtering.

In addition, adjusted p-values are not computed for genes which are thought to have “outliers”.

sum(is.na(res$padj))
## [1] 7607
sum(is.na(res$log2FoldChange))
## [1] 5539
summary(subset(res, is.na(padj))$baseMean)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
## 0.00000 0.00000 0.00000 0.08239 0.11525 0.71155
summary(subset(res, is.na(log2FoldChange))$baseMean)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##       0       0       0       0       0       0
summary(subset(res, is.na(padj) & !is.na(log2FoldChange))$baseMean)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.1152  0.1277  0.2514  0.3031  0.4734  0.7115

Dispersion shrinkage

We can check the dispersion shrinkage by plotting it. This is good practice. It is possible to find datasets where the assumptions are violated, if it looks dramatically different from the one below.

plotDispEsts(dds)

Per default, the ordering of results in R is the same order as the genes. So we have a mix of significant, not significant and not expressed (and therefore not tested) genes

The columns are

  • baseMean: average expression (on count scale) of the gene across all samples.
  • log2FoldChange: the log2FC of the gene across the two groups we compared. This column is harder to interpret if you’re comparing three or more groups with one test.
  • lfcSE: estimated standard error of the log2FoldChange column.
  • `stat: Just log2FoldChange / lfcSE
  • pvalues: unadjusted p-values
  • padj: adjusted p-values. Default method is Benjamini Horchberg, so this targets a False Discovery Rate.

Let’s look at a gene

plotCounts(dds, "19888", intgroup = "group")

We can see how many significant genes we have

sum(res$padj <= 0.1, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 10278

That’s a HUGE amount of differential expression.

We can look at the results ranked by p-value

resOrd <- res[order(res$padj), ]

P-value distribution

It is always a good idea to look at the p-value distribution

hist(res$pvalue, main = "Unadjusted p-values")

Looks good, but reinforces that we have a huge amount of significant genes.

Mean-difference plot

A mean-difference plot is always a good idea to look at. These are also (for historical reasons) called MA plots in genomics.

plotMA(res)

Fold-change shrinkage

DESeq2 also allows for shrinkage of the fold changes. This is in general considered a good idea. Fold-change shrinkage does not affect testing, but it is useful for plotting and ranking genes

resLFC <- lfcShrink(dds, coef = "group_LP_vs_Basal")
## using 'apeglm' for LFC shrinkage. If used in published research, please cite:
##     Zhu, A., Ibrahim, J.G., Love, M.I. (2018) Heavy-tailed prior distributions for
##     sequence count data: removing the noise and preserving large differences.
##     Bioinformatics. https://doi.org/10.1093/bioinformatics/bty895
plotMA(resLFC)
